    align:relation skos:exactMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AISystem ;
    align:target <https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/aiact#AISystem> .

align:49734de1-2a86-4ab8-9f8c-16fa9c35d686 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:a055f89c-234f-4b4a-b6ff-23d23067eb57 ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "The `dpv-aiact:ProhibitedAISystem` is a *specific type* of `AIDOC:AI System`. The AI Act defines systems that are not allowed, which inherently fall under the broader category of all AI Systems. While the lexical similarity is reasonably high, the descriptions clearly indicate a specialization – one describes AI systems generally, while the other focuses on those explicitly prohibited by law."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:narrowMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AISystem ;
    align:target <https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/aiact#ProhibitedAISystem> .

align:57b1daba-d018-4b59-a3d1-9f53fcc0b9ef a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:a055f89c-234f-4b4a-b6ff-23d23067eb57 ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts relate to AI systems and their abilities. `dpv-aiact` provides a more formal, legally-oriented definition aligned with the EU AI Act, detailing autonomy and impact on environments. `AIDOC` is broader, focusing on *what* an AI system can do (capabilities) without specifying the level of autonomy or legal context. While not identical, they are highly related and could be used interchangeably in many contexts concerning AI functionality."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AISystemCapability ;
    align:target <https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/aiact#AISystem> .

align:5c91c364-5136-452a-b9e3-255ac56a4cc8 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:a055f89c-234f-4b4a-b6ff-23d23067eb57 ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts relate to data used for AI training. The AIDOC concept is more descriptive, detailing *what* the data sheet contains (methodologies, hyperparameters etc.), while dpv-aiact focuses on *what* the data *is* – data used for parameter fitting. They are highly related and could be used interchangeably in many contexts, but aren't strictly identical due to this difference in focus."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:TrainingDataSheet ;
    align:target <https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/aiact#TrainingData> .

align:9119fef2-93af-42b4-89a6-d90d6c5c2f36 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:a055f89c-234f-4b4a-b6ff-23d23067eb57 ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts define entities providing AI systems. The AIDOC definition is broader, encompassing developers *or* those placing systems on the market/into service. dpv-aiact focuses specifically on providers integrating an AI model, regardless of origin. While not identical (the 'development' aspect in AIDOC isn’t explicitly present in dpv-aiact), they are highly overlapping and could be used interchangeably in many contexts concerning AI regulation."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AIProvider ;
    align:target <https://w3id.org/dpv/legal/eu/aiact#DownstreamAIProvider> .

